answers.body_markdown:
You can look ahead to see how many items go into the next table row: If the next item is short and if there is another item after that which is short, push two items. Otherwise, just push one:

    while (data.length) {
        let next = data.shift();
        
        if (isshort(next) &amp;&amp; data.length &amp;&amp; isshort(data[0])) {
            table.push([next, data.shift()])
        } else {
            table.push([next])
        }        
    }

Alternatively, and perhaps more generally, you can treat this like a simple word-breaking algorithm: look whether adding the next item will overflow the current line. If yes, wrap:

    function weight(s) {
        return (s.length &lt; 6) ? 1 : 2;
    }

    const cols = 2;                       // number of columns, can be adjusted
    let w = 0;                            // current weighted width of the line
    
    for (let next of data) {
        let u = weight(next);
        
        if (w + u &gt; cols) {
            table.push([]);
            w = 0;
        }
        
        table[table.length - 1].push(next);
        
        w += u;
    }

The number of columns and the weight function can be modified to create tables with more columns.

